tip 1 :
   Indefinite -  in front of word  - en , ei or et  (based on the kjonn)
   definite  - behind the word - en , a or et (based on the kjonn)
   
tip 2 : 
  Indifinte - if you introduce/telling something new - jeg har en sønn på tre år.  (i have a son, who is three year old)
  definite  - if its a known inform to other - Sjefen min er kjempegrei.  (My boss is great).
  
tip 3:
  Indifinite -  --- 
  definite-   after the pronoun - Den , Det ,De , Denne , dette , disse . (det store treet , den lille høna , de små barna ).
  

tip 4:
  Indifinite - if min, din , sin comes in front.  (Dette er min bil).  (this is my car)
  definite-     if min, din , sin comes after. (Dette er bilen min).    (this is my car). norwegian is pretty crazy lol . 
  
 
tip 5:
  Indifinite - etter genitiv 's' (Junis bil er rød).      (juni's car is red)
  definite-  before til in possessive (bilen til juni er rød) (the car of juni is red)
  
 
tip 6:
  Indifinite - if the noun follows following words 
   mange ,flere ,hver ,mye ,ingen ,hvilken/hvilke/hvilket ,noen ,få ,andre ,egen/eget/egne
  definite- if av is added next to above mentioned word then it should follow definite.
     mange av , hele , andre av , få av, hver av , begge , både , hver av, hvilken/hvilke/hvilket av ,  flere av 
     examples 
          Mange biler er blå.     (many cars are blue)
          Mange av bilene er blå. (many of the cars are blue)
          Flere hunder går løse i gatene. (several dogs roam the streets)
          flere av hundene går løse i gatene. (several of the dogs roam the streets)
          
  Tip 7:
    Indefinite - General reference
    definite - specific reference.
    
    
    
    
  8.When these distinctions collide:
  
      Sometimes these the distinctions collide. We may want to start a text by
      talking about a specific university. Then, the university is both new
      information (= indefinite form) and specific (= definite form). It is difficult to
      give strict rules for the priority between the distinctions, but usually the
      priority is like this:
      1. One among many vs. unique
      2. General vs. specific
      3. New information vs. known information
      Therefore, a text about a specific university must start with the definite form:
      Jeg studerer på universitetet i Trondheim. Det heter NTNU.
      Because of this order of priority, we also need the indefinite form in the
      example above Oslo er en by i Norge. We have a geographical specification (i
      Norge), but Oslo is one among many cities, and that is given more priority than
      the geographical specification.

 9.Idiomatic expressions:

      In some expressions we usually use the indefinite form regardless of the rules
      above. Her are a few examples:

      gå på kurs/jobb/arbeid
      gå/være på kafé/kino/restaurant...
      reise med buss/fly/tog...
      ta buss/fly/tog...
      kjøre bil
      spille gitar/piano/tromme...
      ha tid til
      til frokost/lunsj/middag
      In many other expressions we usually use the definite, as in these examples:
      gå på skolen/i barnehagen
      studere/jobbe på universitetet
      gå/være i kirka
      en gang i uka/måneden/året
      Here are two frequent time expressions with the indefinite and definite form
      respectively:
      om sommeren (= hver sommer)
      i sommer (= denne sommeren)
      We use the indefinite form in the name of many famous sites. Here, the
      definite form may change the meaning of the phrase:
      Det hvite hus (= the house of the president of the USA)
      Det hvite huset (= a specific house which is white)
      Den røde plass (=Cremlin square in Moscow)
      Den røde plassen (= a place which is coloured red)
 
  
